inkled with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Points</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  In order for an NPC to move from its current location to another location, for example, to attack an enemy, it first finds and moved toward the nearest <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Point</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  From there, it moves to the nearest <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Point</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that is closer to its goal, travelling from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Point</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Point</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> until it arrives near its goal.<br>
<br>
The purpose of these <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Points</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is to simplify programming the behavior of NPCs.  In particular, it eliminates the need for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Collision Detection</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for NPCs, that is, there is no need to prevent NPCs from going through walls or other obstacles.  These <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Points</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are laid out by the designers of the zone, and vary greatly in quality.  Some places in some zones are notorious for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bad Pathing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: poorly chosen <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Path Points</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that cause NPCs to wander great distances, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;warp&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or teleport, or even despawn, including pets.<br>
<br>
Before <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Great Patch</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the fear of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bad Pathing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> greatly limited the use of pets, as the risk of a sudden pet detour aggroing distant mobs and causing a wipeout prevented all but the most reputable pet owners from using pets in those places.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1633<br> <font color=#333333>(7/9/02 12:47:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=107.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Hate: By the power of Her Regent, Lord Innoruuk</span><hr size=1> NPCs maintain a ranked <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of immediate enemies, and, in general, will chase down and attack whichever enemy within <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Attack Range</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is currently the highest on their list.  The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is constantly changing as characters against the NPC and its allies.  The following discussion is simplified somewhat to focus on pets and their behaviour, but applies, with some modification and caveats, to NPCs in general.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Hate</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Direct and indirect actions against an NPC add a specific amount of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to the score of that individual on the NPC's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The value of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> added appears to decay over time, so that more recent actions weigh more heavily than those a while ago.  That is, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> appears to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;age,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and become weaker over time.  That is why one must be careful how often one nukes an enemy.<br>
<br>
The primary determinant of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate Value</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of an attack is the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>potential</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> damage that attack could have normally done.  Thus <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> ignores both resists and criticals.  All attacks with the same weapon or spell generate the same amount of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> regardless of how much damage they actually dealt, even if they miss or are fully resisted.  Spells that do not do damage have a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> value assigned to them.  Some, like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Tash</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Slow</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spells, have a high <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> values.  Others, like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Cancel Magic</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Malosini</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, have a low <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> value.  Healing and buffing an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> NPC</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s enemies also generates <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Taunting a second time:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  When a character successfully <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Taunts</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> an NPC, that character moves up to the top of that NPC's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but just barely.  By default, pets have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Taunt On</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which means they constantly try to taunt their enemies.  However, because of special rules designed primarily to prevent abuses of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Charmed Pets</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, an NPC will almost always chose to attack a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Player Character</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> if one is within melee distance, even when a pet is at the top of its <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  It is not known precisely what these <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;special rules&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are, but in practice they prevent pets from tanking in the presence of player characters within melee distance of the mob.<br>
<br>
Any creature that attacks a pet's owner is added to the pet's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Pets cannot attack a creature which has been <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> charmed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by a player character, but such creatures remain <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (?)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on the pet's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
If a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mezzed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> enemy reaches the top of a pet's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the pet removes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (?)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> from its <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> instead of attacking.<br>
